{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_beargrass_ver01/data/sn86075096/00340581702/1948100101/0834.xml":{"full_text":"The Editor's Page\nIt Is the Other Fellow\nHO'S TO blame for the high cost of\nliving? No. Wait. We're not going\ninto that again. The subject will be aired\nthoroughly and inconclusively from now on\nthrough election time and after that until\nit comes time to argue who caused the next\ndepression. Besides, the answer is obvious.\nIt is the other fellow.\nBut when the conversation does inevi\ntably come around to the subject, and par\nticularly when it brings in farm price sup\nports for consideration as the possible cul\nprit, here are a few points that can add to\nthe discussion though they won't settle it.\nFirst of all, the principle of supports is\nnot really an issue in the present cam\npaign. Both parties are committed at least\nto the principle. Thus the farm and ranch\noperator who is convinced that support of\nagricultural prices is fundamental to the\neconomic health of the nation and his neigh\nbor across the road who is equally con\nvinced that supports are only a phase of\nbureaucratic control should confine their\narguing for the time to questions of how\nmuch support and how implemented?\nFurther, reports that are being bandied\nabout as to the possible costs of maintaining\nsupports this year or any year should be\nconsidered with caution. One estimate is\nthat the government may be called upon to\nW\nIt's Time to Cull That Herd\nT HIS is it. Now is the time to trim that\ncattle herd if it is just a little bigger\nthan its average range and feed supply\nwarrants or to cull the herd and replace\nwith better quality units if inferior animals\nhave been carried along during these times\nwhen any critter is worth money and feed\nhas been comparatively plentiful.\nSo say the experts. They have said it be\nfore. In fact they have said it pretty regu\nlarly through each of the past several years\nof good livestock prices and good grass and\nhay production in Montana and Wyoming.\nEach year the advice has been given on the\nsound premise that any time the price is\nhigh is a good time to sell. Other arguments\nwere that, since the present year was a\ngood one for range and feed, there was at\nleast a 50-50 chance that the coming one\nwould not be and, further, that a recession\ncould always be suspected of being just\naround the corner.\nToday the advice is based on the same\npremises, and they may or may not be any\nmore valid now than before. Prices are still\ngood, so it is still a good time to sell. Wheth\ner next year will be dry or whether it will\nbring a lower national income with conse\nChemicals Contribute to Crop\nfp'HERE is no chemical that means as much\nto Montana crops as good old H20,\nwater. How Montana land can respond to\nits treatment is happily demonstrated by\nthis year's record crops.\nBut the showers of weed and insect con\ntrol chemicals that were applied to the\nfields this year also contributed enormously\nto the good harvest. What portion of the rec\nput out as much as $1,500,000,000 under the\nloan program in support of grain prices.\nThis may be true, but the huge figure\nshould not carelessly be accepted as a cost,\nsince the loans will be paid back. Only ad\nministrative charges and possible defaults,\nif any, will be cost. The entire support pro\ngram last year, including the much pub\nlicized potato campaign did cost the gov\nernment $175,000,000.\nFinally, the farmer and rancher are not\nforgetting that support prices are not fixed\nprices but are geared to parity, which is\nthe ratio of the prices of things the farmer\nhas to sell to those of things he has to buy.\nSupport prices stay up only if other\nprices do.\nAs the present law stands, support prices\non basic commodities are to be maintained\nat 90 percent of parity until 1950. There is\nsome agitation now to lower the parity\nutes before then, but whether the 90 per\ncent parity level prevails or not, next year's\nloan or support levels are likely to be low\ner than this year. The USDA has estimated\nthat lower prices for feed grains and feed\nstuffs may reduce the parity index enough\nto push the wheat loan level down 5 to 10\ncents a bushel next year. Thus, the farmer\nhimself has brought about the first reduc\ntion of supports.\nOne positive factor does now exist, how\never, that would seem bound to affect the\npicture. The 1948 record crops have brought\ny j.\nus suddenly close again to a surplus condi\ntion. Feed prices have tumbled, and since\nmeat is simply converted feed, the differ\nence should show in a predictable length of\ntime. Again the experts say now that it\nshould be by early 1950. It will be longer\nthan that before the conversion of feed into\nquent drop in demand for meat is still a\nmatter of conjecture.\nmore beef can come about, but the conver\nsion into increased supplies of pork and\npoultry can be rapid and soon affect the to\ntal meat situation.\nThere are not too many cattle. Montana\nherds have leveled off at about 10 percent\nunder the all-time peak of about 2,000,000\nhead in 1945. In view of the sharp decline\nin sheep numbers, the present cattle popu\nlation is probably well within the reason\nable carrying capacity of our ranges. But\nthere is probably also need for readjust\nment of numbers in some individual opera\ntions and there is always the possibility of\nimprovement of quality in any operation.\nThis is it. The time for trimming and\nculling for more efficient operation is here.\nThat time is always here.\nord yields can be credited directly to the\nuse of weed chemicals will probably never\nbe known, but the share is unquestionably\nlarge. This was a good year for weeds, and\nthe stories are numerous this year, as last\nof weed chemical applications making the\ndifference between what might have been\nno crop at all and a good crop.\nTwo years ago was also a good year for\nweeds. It might be labeled the last year\nB. C. (before chemicals), for only a little ex\nperimental spraying and dusting was done.\nAnd that year farmers were harvesting so\nmuch weed seed with their grain that they\nfound it profitable to screen the grain and\nmarket the weed seed for vegetable oil pro\nduction. This year entire crops of thou\nsands of bushels have been marketed with\nout a single truck load being docked,\nded yield, ease of harvesting and increased\nvalue through elimination of dockage can\nscarcely be overestimated.\nAnd the same assessment of value can b\u00ab\nThe contribution of weed chemicals in ad\nplaced upon new insecticides. Tests have\nshown that alfalfa fields treated with DDT\nand other chemicals have not only out\nyielded untreated fields but have produced\na better quality of hay. The saving of seed\ntremendous,\nyields from the attacks of insects has been\nRecent years have shown that plenty of\ngood old water plus the chemicals can work\nwonders. What the chemicals can contrib\nute when there is less moisture remain*\nto be seen,\nwere greater than the gross farm income\nin any year between World war 1 and\nWorld war 2, the bureau of agricultural\neconomics reports. It warns that if price*\nfall, expenses will still tend to remain at\nrelatively high levels, making careful man\nStraws in the Wind\nCosts of producing crops in 1947 and 1948\nagement essential and restriction of cash\noutlays advisable.\nPoultry producers of the nation are urged\nby the U. S. department of agriculture to de\nvelop a production force of 425,000,000 hens\nand pullets by January. Egg consumption\nh as averaged 380 per capita during 1947, the\ndepartment reports, and wams that a drop\nof only 1,000,000 hens will mean one egg a\nday less for everyone next year,\nLast April the USDA asked for a 10 per\ncent increase in the fall pig crop, but with\ncorn supplies short and the hog-corn price\nratio far below average, the June pig report\nshowed no increase. Now the recommenda\ntion is for the largest spring pig crop in\nhistory, a 17 percent increase. With corn\nplentiful, the goal this time may be reached,\nFarm real estate values in the first half\nof the year averaged 2 percent above the\n1920 peak, 7 percent above a year earlier\nand more than double the 1935-39 average.\nMontana was among states in which an in\ncrease of more than 5 percent for the first\nsix months of the year was noted.\nMontana Farmer-Stockman\n\u2014COVERS MONTANA AND NORTHERN WYOMING\u2014\nOFFICE: m 4th 8t. N., Great Falla, Montai\u00bb\nLESTES COLE\nDON R. BOSLEY\nLARRY GILL\nJERRY LESTER\nEditor and Manager\nAssistant Editor\nLivestock Editor\nRevins Report\u00ab*\nDepartment Editors: AMY MARTIN, Rural Homes Depart\nment; DR. HOWARD WELCH. Veterinary Department:\nRALPH D. MERCER, Solis and Crops; H. E. CUSHMAN,\nPoultry; I, W. DICKERSON. Farm Mechanics; DR. JOHN\nW. HOLLAND. Thoughts on Life: GILBERT GDSLER.\nMarket Analyst.\nAdrertislne Representatives: Western Associated Fans\nPapers\u2014CHICAGO 4: Fred Tool, National Adv. Manager,\n28 K Jackson. NEW YORK 18: John W. Fox. Manager, SO\u00ae\nFifth Avenue: SAN FRANCISCO \u00cf: J. J. Mattns, Man\nager. VOT Sharon Building.\nMember of Associated Farm Papers, Audit Bureau mt\nCirculations and Agricultural Publishers Association\nSUBSCRIPTION PRICE\u2014 S3 for five years, S2 for three\nyears, *1 for one year: Canadian, one year. $2.00.\nRENEWALS AND CHANGES\u2014If the date on your label\nla not changed within three weeks after sending in\nyour remittance, please write us. If you wish a ehang\u00ab\nin address, give both new and old postoffices.\nADVERTISING\u2014Pull information regarding advertising\nrates etc., eent on application. Subscribers are requested\nto mention promptly to us any advertiser who fails\nto live up to his advertising agreement.\nTot. M, No. S","height":"15903","width":"11037"}}
